{"title_page": "Carolinian people", "text_new": "{{Expert needed|Ethnic groups|talk=Accuracy Dispute and Expert Needed|reason=Badly written and claimed to be a matriarchal society while having no source. It can even claimed it is a patriarchal society.|date=October 2019}}\n{{Disputed|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{infobox ethnic group\n| group = Carolinians\n| image = Carolinian people in 1915.jpg\n| caption = Carolinian family in 1915\n| population = Over 8,500\n| popplace = [[Saipan]], [[Northern Mariana Islands]], [[Caroline Islands]], [[Guam]]\n| langs = [[Carolinian language|Carolinian]], [[Chamorro language|Chamorro]], [[English language|American English]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| rels = [[Roman Catholic]] & [[Traditional religion]]s|\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| related_groups = \n}}\n\nThe '''Carolinian''', or '''''Refaluwasch''''' (Pronounced ''Ri-fa-lu-wash'') '''people''' are an [[Austronesian people|Austronesian]] ethnic group who originated in [[Oceania]], in the eastern [[Caroline Islands]], with a total population of around 8,500 people. They are also known as '''''Remathau''''' (Pronounced ''Ray-ma-thow'')<ref>{{Citation|last=Pacific Students Media|title=Remathau Graduation 2015|date=2015-06-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aOHbcGPaSso&t=129s|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> in the Yap's outer islands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/articles/aapi-theme-study-essay-12-pacific-islander-heritage.htm|title=Essay 12: Pacific Islanders in the US and their Heritage: Making Visible the Visibly Absent (U.S. National Park Service)|website=nps.gov|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref><ref>Falanruw. Marjorie V. C. & Ruegorang, Francis. Dynamics Of An Island Agroecosystem Where to Now? ''U. S. Forest Service'', n. d. https://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/falanruw/psw_2015_falanruw001.pdf</ref> The Carolinian word means \"People of the Deep Sea.\" It is thought that their ancestors may have originally immigrated from [[Asia]] and [[Indonesia]] to [[Micronesia]] around 2,000 years ago. Their primary language is [[Carolinian language|Carolinian]], called ''Refaluwasch'' by native speakers, which has a total of about 5,700 speakers. The Carolinians have a [[matriarchy|matriarchal]] society in which respect is a very important factor in their daily lives, especially toward the [[matriarch]]s. Most Carolinians are of the [[Roman Catholic]] faith.\n\nThe immigration of Carolinians to [[Saipan]] began in the early 19th century, after the [[Spain|Spanish]] killed most of the local population of [[Chamorro people|Chamorro]] natives, reducing them to just 3,700. They began immigrating by sailing mostly from small [[canoe]]s via islands which were previously devastated by a [[typhoon]]. The Carolinians have a much darker complexion than the native [[Chamorro people|Chamorros]].\n\n== Genetics ==\nCarolinians from Saipan have the same lineages with Remathau on the outer islands of Yap.\n\nSome of the people on the islands are Chamolinians which are a mixture of Chamorro and Carolinian heritage.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=VILAR|first=MIGUEL G.|last2=CHAN|first2=CHIM W|last3=SANTOS|first3=DANA R|last4=LYNCH|first4=DANIEL|last5=SPATHIS|first5=RITA|last6=GARRUTO|first6=RALPH M|last7=LUM|first7=J KOJI|date=2013|title=The Origins and Genetic Distinctiveness of the Chamorros of the Marianas Islands: An mtDNA Perspective|journal=American Journal of Human Biology|volume=25|issue=1|pages=116\u2013122|doi=10.1002/ajhb.22349|issn=1042-0533|pmc=4335639|pmid=23180676}}</ref>\n\nThe Carolinians in the CNMI have a high rate of macrosomia which is where the infant is born abnormally large.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/fetal-macrosomia/symptoms-causes/syc-20372579|title=Fetal macrosomia - Symptoms and causes|website=Mayo Clinic|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe people have a long history from Caroline Islands and CNMI too the present in the 21st century.\n\n=== Pre-Spanish era (antiquity-1697) ===\n[[File:Caroline Islands-map.gif|thumb|The islands were the Refaluwasch came from were over 400 miles from what is now the CNMI.]]\nThey have a history stretching back over 3000 years. The Carolinian people had contact with the Chamorro people for years. They had a long history of traveling from the Caroline Islands to what is now Guam. \"Pre-contact\" Carolinian designed pestles, hooks for fishing, and rings made out of shells found on the ground and beneath it show contact between the two groups.\n\nThey built canoes that would have a small roof. The roof only went over less than have of the canoe. The sides could be different colors. The boat could fit over 9 adults in it.<ref>Todino, Junhan B. \"Carolinian Affairs Office float leads parade competition\" ''The Guam Daily Post,''https://www.postguam.com/news/cnmi/carolinian-affairs-office-float-leads-parade-competition/article_ac0f5916-8e43-11e8-a718-d78243d7dab8.html</ref>\n\nCenturies ago they used sea-lanes based off memorize information from the prior generation.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FJ9ULYwX3zgC&pg=PA447&lpg=PA447&dq=chamolinian&source=bl&ots=3g4nRr0x2x&sig=ACfU3U0I-JCe7P6G6wAi3IEbblG_y3DRGA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiszIaU6aviAhVFRKwKHYLOCB84KBDoATAEegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=carolinian&f=false|title=The Cambridge History of the Pacific Islanders|last=Meleisea|first=Malama|last2=Linnekin|first2=Jocelyn|date=2004-03-25|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521003544|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBefore colonial times a system called sawei was practiced. The word sawei means Yapese chief, conqueror, tyrant. This involved the Carolinians gathering once every two or three years in Yap. This system may have existed before the year 1600. More on this is discuss in the religion section.\n\nTrade between the two groups went on even during the Spanish occupation of Guam.\n\n=== Typhoon devastation & Spanish era (1697-1899) ===\nIn the late 1600s leprosy was present in the Marianas. The Spaniards tried to deal with this by quarantining lepers to Saipan and Tinian. These islands were isolated. Spaniards brought Carolinians to these islands to help the hospitals holding the patients with leprosy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uog.edu/uogpress/publications/marc/lepers-in-the-mariana-islands-during-the-spanish-administration-1668-1898-addenda.php|title=Lepers in the Mariana Islands During the Spanish Administration 1668-1898 & Addenda (1899-1949)|website=uog.edu|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\nChamorro sargento mayor Lu\u00eds de Torres became an important source for people who wanted information of the Carolinian people.\n\nDuring this time the people built a boat called Waa (canoe). This is a boat built for the sea. They were for transporting cargo and passengers over long distances.<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Waa (Canoe) of the Caroline Islands|date=2009-10-13|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/4010603376/|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>\n\nIn Guam, Carolinians came to Talofofo Bay in 1788. They were on a voyage. The reason why they stopped there was because they wanted iron. This kind of trade hadn't occurred in over a hundred years in Guam since the military conflicts between Spanish and Chamorros.\n[[File:Talofofo Bay (17420120219).jpg|thumb|This is what Talofofo Bay looks like.]]\nIn the 19th century the Refaluwasch moved from Elato and Satawal islands in the East and West part of the Carolinian islands<ref>Ristroph, Elizabeth Barrett. \"The Survival Of Customary Law In The Northern Mariana Islands.\" ''Chicago-Kent School of Law Illinois Institute of Technology.'' 2007 http://studentorgs.kentlaw.iit.edu/jicl/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/01/Ristroph_customary_nmi.pdf</ref> to what is now Northern Mariana Islands.<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Talofofo Bay|date=2009-10-06|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/3986693874/|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>   \n[[File:Elato Lamolior Landsat.jpg|left|thumb|This is an image of Elato from outer space.]]\n[[File:Micro Beach (530316786).jpg|left|thumb|This beach is where the two chiefs came. Aghurubw loved this place.]]\nThe two islands were destroyed by typhoon. Refaluwasch were starving during this time. Chief Nguschul of Elato along with Chief Aghurubw of Satawal led the people to the NMI. They landed at Micro Beach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/editorials/61221-refaluwasch-come-to-saipan|title=BC's Tales of the Pacific: Refaluwasch come to Saipan|last=Variety|first=Marianas|website=Marianas Variety|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref> After coming to Saipan they built a village called Arabwal.  Right now this area is in American Memorial Park.<ref>\"A Living Legacy.\" ''NPS,''[https://www.nps.gov/amme/planyourvisit/upload/AMME_S2_interactive.pdf https://www.nps.gov/amme/planyourvisit/upload/AMME_S2_interactive.pdf.] Accessed 4 April 2019.</ref> This was not the only village built. The other one Ppiyal Oolang.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IVVQ46epBqwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=micronesian+legends#v=onepage&q=micronesian%20legends&f=false|title=Micronesian Legends|last=Flood|first=Bo|last2=Strong|first2=Beret E.|last3=Flood|first3=William|date=2002|publisher=Bess Press|isbn=9781573061292}}</ref> This area is where Nguschul and his group settled. The Carolinians continued to come here in the 100s as well as other areas such as Guam and Tinian.<ref name=\":6\">Riesenberg, Saul H. & Kaneshiro, Shiegeru. ''A Caroline Islands Script''. Smithsonian Institution, n. d.  https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/22111/bae_bulletin_173_1960_60_269-333.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y</ref>  \n[[File:Saipan from ISS 2.png|left|thumb|This is an aerial view of Saipan the island the people came too after the islands were hit by the typhoon.]]\nThe Spanish allowed them to keep their culture.\n\nDuring the mid 1800s Carolinians moved to Tamuning due to a 1849 typhoon which devastated their land.<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Carolinians, 1902|date=2009-10-06|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/3985939473/|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time they took over [http://www.soest.hawaii.edu/pfrp/reprints/Amesbury_Terra_Australis39_2013.pdf inter-island] travel during the latter half of the 18th century and 19th century. They used a ship called ''banca'' to travel.\n\nIn 1865 265 Carolinians were transferred from the Carolines by Englishman George Johnston. He moved them to Pagan.<ref name=\":2\">Amesbury, Judith R. \"What are all those people doing in that ecosystem?\" Scientific and Statistical Committee Western Pacific Fishery Management Council, NOAA, n. d.https://www.pifsc.noaa.gov/media/news/mariana_archipelago_ecosystem_science_implementation_plan_workshop_amesbury.pdf</ref>\n\nThe Tanapag village was setup by some Refaluwasch who left Tinian island in 1879.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nTen years later in 1889 Governor Olive had the Refaluwasch on Tinian relocate to Tanapag.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== German period (1899-1914) ===\nSpain sold the Northern Mariana Islands to Germany in 1899, after losing Guam to the United States in 1898. This area became known as the German Northern Marianas. This was the shortest period a country controlled this area. They didn't change the culture of the Carolinians a lot but did bring in new ways of schooling, bureaucracy, architecture, and administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guampedia.com/pop-cultures-cnmi/|title=\u00bb POP Cultures: CNMI|website=guampedia.com|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref> The legal system was transparent towards both Carolinians and Chamorros.\n\nGeorg Fritz on November 17, 1899 became the first district officer of this area. He set up programs which brought the Carolinians and Chamorro people living on the islands together.\n\nMarriages between German settlers or colonial officers and Carolinians at Saipan occurred. The marriage did not allow for citizenship for either the Carolinian partner or children. This was the same for Chamorro people.\n\nCarolinians were peaceful towards the Germans.\n\nThe population measurement in 1901 for these individuals are 772. The last population count the Germans did in 1914 recorded 1,109 of them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arif|first=Sigit Supadmo|last2=Prabowo|first2=Abi|last3=Suprapto|first3=Anjar|last4=Kurniawan|first4=Judy|date=2007-03-01|title=Irrigation asset management plan: concept development and its implementation in Indonesia|journal=Jurnal Keteknikan Pertanian|volume=21|pages=45\u201356|doi=10.19028/jtep.21.1.45-56|issn=0216-3365}}</ref>\n\nCarolinians didn't own land during this time unlike the Chamorros living here.\n\n=== US Naval era (1899-1903) ===\n[[File:Richard Leary.jpg|thumb|An image of former Governor Leary.]]\nIn Guam the people were made to adopt Western ways because of the U.S. Naval Administration.\n\nOne example of this was banning [[nudity]]. In Guam the first American governor was [[Richard P. Leary]] (1899-1900). He issued an order where Carolinian women in Guam weren't allowed to be naked when ever he visited. This was done away with by Governor [[William E. Sewell]] (1903-1904). The men were not allowed to be naked either. Many went to Saipan to avoid doing this. The constant nudity of the people bothered the second American governor [[Seaton Schroeder]] (1900-1903) so much that he decided to move them off the island. They were sent to CNMI through an agreement with the Germans who controlled those islands. They wanted additional laborers.\n\n=== Japanese Administration & Occupation (1914-1945) ===\nJapan took over the Mariana Islands in 1914. They were able to keep it due to the [https://www.britannica.com/place/Northern-Mariana-Islands#ref273250 Treaty of Versailles].\n[[File:American Memorial Park.jpg|left|thumb|This is located on Saipan and is the location of Arabwal. The names of Carolinians who died during WWII are inscribed in granite panels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/amme/learn/photosmultimedia/photogallery.htm|title=Photo Gallery - American Memorial Park (U.S. National Park Service)|last=Saipan|first=Mailing Address: P. O. Box 5198|last2=Us|first2=MP 96950 Phone:234-7207 x2002 Contact|website=nps.gov|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/amme/learn/historyculture/upload/Marianas-Memorial-Listing.pdf|title=Marianas Memorial|date=2019-05-15|website=National Park Service|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Chamorro and Kanaka girls in 1930s.jpg|thumb|Under Japan Carolinians in kanakas like the one on the right still practice their culture. The fashion concerning the leaf structures was even present then.|alt=]]\nThe Carolinians had villages which the Japanese called kanakas. These villages were controlled by sosoncho and soncho. Sosoncho is a general village chieftain. A soncho is a village chieftain. These chieftains didn't always have position under the traditional tribal patterns.\n\nWhile the Japanese controlled these islands they used these people as laborers for mining and handling phosphate ore. One of the mines was in Angaur under the Palau group.<ref name=\":6\" /> Carolinians were not treated as well as the Chamorros who worked with them. The Japanese and other colonial powers during this time (WWI-WWII) would not allow Carolinians to do canoe navigation over large distances.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time a term was used to refer to the Micronesian people under Japanese control which was 'Tomin.' Tomin meant inhabitants of the land. The Carolinian and Chamorro people viewed this as a put down since Japanese used it as part of discrimination. The people were kept under strict surveillance.<ref>Guampedia. ''\"Marianas History Conference III - Part 3\"'' issuu''.'' 2018, https://issuu.com/guampedia/docs/mhc_iii_2017_3</ref> They were enslaved in 1944.<ref name=\":0\">Collier, R. Navigating Modernity / The Carolinians, a tiny group of islanders on Saipan, in the western Pacific, have seen their ancient culture succumb to consumerism. As they try to salvage what they can of their past, they are helping to lead a cultural revival am. ''SF Gate.'' 1999, https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Navigating-Modernity-The-Carolinians-a-tiny-3774200.php</ref> During this time few in this indigenous community served as scouts for the U.S. military. They served in the U.S. Marines.\n\nOn Saipan some Refaluwasch families were under an American military government. Some of them were in Camp Susupe. They were in a Chamorro-Carolinian area of the Camp.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=The Northern Mariana Islands Judiciary: A Historical Overview|last=|first=|publisher=Northern Marianas Judiciary Historical Society|year=2011|isbn=978-0-615-42762-1|location=http://www.justice.gov.mp/uploads/History_Book_-_ch1-4.pdf|pages=}}</ref> <gallery>\nFile:Camp susupe sign.JPG|The camp was used for Refaluwasch people as well as Japanese.\n</gallery>Some Refaluwasch were restricted from returning to their lands during this occupation. One of the reasons why they were interned was because the United States government wanted them to learn English as well as American political and social life. They were allowed to farm and fish before the evening. They had to return to the Camp when night came.\n\nOn Saipan during April 1945 there were 810 Refaluwasch on the island. Later in September of that more people of that group were brought into Saipan.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAfter the Japanese surrender Refaluwasch were allowed to [http://www.anthropology.hawaii.edu/people/emeritus/white/NEH_2010/required%20pdfs/Camacho_chap_5_ed_nov24.pdf return]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} to their lands.\n\n=== Post World War II (1945-present) ===\nThe people didn't object to the edicts of the U.S. military authorities. They were thankful for the basic necessities provided by Naval Military Government. The authorities founded a police force consisting of Carolinians and Chamorros for Camp Susupe and Chalan Kanoa. It was called Native Police and was 87 strong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/letters-to-the-editor/54440-a-saipan-marine-died|title=A Saipan Marine died|last=Variety|first=Marianas|website=Marianas Variety|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref>\n\nUnder the Naval Military Government Carolinian families in certain cases adopted orphans of Korean or Japanese descent. They were orphaned because of WWII.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThey have served in the Vietnam War. Only less than a [https://sablan.house.gov/vietnam-veterans-cnmi-get-congressional-tribute 100] are known.\n\nBefore 2004 the Carolinians and Chamorro people were competing with each other before banding together. This is sometimes called Chamolinian. They did this to challenge what they call outsiders. Outsiders involve Filipinos and Japanese among other groups of immigrants and/or migrants.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FJ9ULYwX3zgC&pg=PA447&lpg=PA447&dq=chamolinian&source=bl&ots=3g4nRr0x2x&sig=ACfU3U0I-JCe7P6G6wAi3IEbblG_y3DRGA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiszIaU6aviAhVFRKwKHYLOCB84KBDoATAEegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=chamolinian&f=false|title=The Cambridge History of the Pacific Islanders|last=Meleisea|first=Malama|date=2004-03-25|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521003544|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018 Refaluwasch in the Marianas have one of the highest rates of service in the U.S. military.\n\nIn 2018 former Acting Governor of Northern Mariana Islands Victor Hocog [https://www.postguam.com/news/cnmi/september-proclaimed-chamorro-and-carolinian-cultural-heritage-month/article_bc820b5e-aff9-11e8-970b-f3ce9c49a4fc.html signed] a proclamation to make September Chamorro and Carolinian Heritage Month. In the month you have special day called Chief Aghurubw Day. The former is held on Sept. 29. Chief Aghurubw and his people travel from Satawal to Saipan before setting up the first Carolinian settlement in CNMI in 1815.\n\n==== Population & Economic Figures ====\nThe population in 1999 on the CNMI was 3,500.\n\nCarolinians due to Compact of Free Association have increased greatly on [https://www.guampedia.com/carolinians-on-guam/ Guam]. As of the 2000 U.S. census the population is around 11,000.\n\nThey are 4.6% of the population on CNMI. According to the 2010 American FactFinder profile on CNMI the Carolinians number over 2,400.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_DPMP_MPDP1&prodType=table|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U. S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106145130/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_DPMP_MPDP1&prodType=table|archive-date=2018-11-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Saipan they are 20% of the population.<ref name=\":4\">Guampedia. Chamorro Cultural Values Workshop-Summary Workshop Report. ''Guampedia, 2016,'' http://www.guampedia.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Chamorro_Cultural_Values_Workshop.pdf</ref> The population in the United States has increased a lot.<ref>Hixson, Lindsay, Hepler, Bradford B. & Kim, Myoung O. The Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Population: 2010. ''Census,'' May 2012, https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/briefs/c2010br-12.pdf</ref> Outside the CNMI and Guam in the United States Washington State has the biggest population of them.<ref name=\":5\">EPIC & Asian Americans Advancing Justice. Native Hawaiians & Pacific Islanders A Community Of Contrasts 2014 In The United States. ''Empower PDI,'' 2014, https://www.empoweredpi.org/uploads/1/1/4/1/114188135/a_community_of_contrasts_nhpi_us_2014-1.pdf</ref> The population in the state is 127. In Seattle there is 116 of them.<ref name=\":5\" /> Concerning age 40% of the people in this group are less than 18 while only 2% of this group are over 65.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nDuring the late 1990s it was estimated they had 20 percent unemployment. Also during this time they were behind the Chamorros in terms of economics. The Chamorro people were more economical development than they were. This has been going on for a long time in their community. They were susceptible to progress' bad effects.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Navigating-Modernity-The-Carolinians-a-tiny-3774200.php|title=Navigating Modernity / The Carolinians, a tiny group of islanders on Saipan, in the western Pacific, have seen their ancient culture succumb to consumerism. As they try to salvage what they can of their past, they are helping to lead a cultural revival am - SFChronicle.com|date=1999-03-07|website=sfgate.com|access-date=2019-04-15}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2010 U.S. Census the people along with other Micronesian groups have lower home owner ship than the many other ethnic groups in the country. They are mainly renters.<ref name=\":5\" /> Their household sizes are 3.9. They have bigger household sizes than Latinos. Only 14% of them are homeowners while the rest are renters.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThey make up 2% of the population in Palau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/ps.html|title=Australia - Oceania :: Palau \u2014 The World Factbook - Central Intelligence Agency|website=cia.gov|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Metzgar|first=Eric|date=November 2016|title=Carolinian Voyaging In The New Millennium|url=http://marshall.csu.edu.au/MJHSS/Issue2006/MJHSS2006_117.pdf|journal=Micronesian Journal of the Humanities and Social Sciences|volume=5|pages=293\u2013305|via=}}</ref>\n\n==== Resistance to U.S. militarization ====\nDespite the fact there are high rates of service for the military in this community there has been resistance to buildup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://csudh.kanopy.com/welcome/video/insular-empire-america-mariana-islands|title=Welcome to California State University Dominguez Hills {{!}} Kanopy|website=csudh.kanopy.com|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/guampedia/docs/0608-fanohge_famalao_an|title=Fanohge Famal\u00e5o'an & Fan'tachu Fama'lauan|website=Issuu|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> Refaluwasch women are using different ways to resist military buildup in the Marianas Archipelago. They have used digital, legal, political, and spiritual methods to resist this. They are using lawsuits supported by the National Environmental Protection Act. They are using this against the Department of Defense (DoD) and Department of the Navy.\n\n== Politics ==\n[[File:Benigno Fitial and Josie Fitial.jpg|thumb|A picture of the former governor Fitial and his wife Josie Fitial.]]\nThere has been efforts to bring the Marianas together. In the 1960s people submitted a resolution against putting the Marianas under one government. The Carolinians in the Northern Marianas desired stronger ties with Refaluwasch abroad in Micronesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guampedia.com/history-of-efforts-to-reunify-the-mariana-islands/|title=\u00bb History of Efforts to Reunify the Mariana Islands|website=guampedia.com|access-date=2019-05-16}}</ref> A lot of them wanted CNMI to be freely associated with the U. S.\n\nThe population is represented in the legislature however the Chamorro people are dominant in politics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Northern-Mariana-Islands|title=Northern Mariana Islands {{!}} history - geography|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\nElias Parung Sablan became Mayor of Saipan in 1945.\n\n[[Benigno Fitial|Benigno R. Fitial]] (1945- ) became the CNMI's first governor of Carolinian descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/58540-refaluwasch-gather-to-express-support-for-heinz|title=Refaluwasch gather to express support for Heinz|last=Variety|first=Marianas|website=Marianas Variety|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n[[File:Timothy Villagomez.jpg|thumb|Picture of Villagomez.]]\nLieutenant Governor [[Timothy Villagomez|Timothy P. Villagomez]] served under Fitial.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mycnmi.blogspot.com/2007/04/1st-ever-carolinian-language-symposium.html|title=.: 1st Ever Carolinian Language Symposium April 18 & 19, 2007|last=Blogger|first=Cnmi|date=2007-04-18|website=.|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/tim-villagomez-okd-to-travel-to-ph/|title=Tim Villagomez OK'd to travel to PH|date=2018-11-18|website=Saipan News, Headlines, Events, Ads {{!}} Saipan Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>\n\nCinta Kaipat served in CNMI House of Representatives in the 15th CNMI Legislature.\n\n[[Joe Camacho|Joseph James Norita Camacho]] was a member of 16th CNMI House of Representatives and held the position as House Floor Leader. He was elected to this position in 2007.\n\nIn the Obama Administration a Refaluwasch women named Rellani Bennett Ogumoro served as the Policy Advisor for the Domestic Policy Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@ObamaWhiteHouse/indigenous-peoples-voices-from-the-white-house-fe22d7eb2b2f|title=Indigenous Peoples: Voices from the White House|last=House|first=The Obama White|date=2016-09-26|website=Medium|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.law.asu.edu/apps/directory/?Letter=O|title=Sandra Day O'Connor College of Law|website=apps.law.asu.edu|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref><ref>Navigating a Political Relationship: Indigenous and American in the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands. ''Arizona State University'', n. d. https://asuevents.asu.edu/sites/default/files/rellaniogumoroll3.pdf</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Managaha SW 2014.JPG|thumb|View of a portion of Managaha Island.]]\nTheir culture originated from the islands Yap and Chuuk in what is now the Federated States of Micronesia. The present day generation as of 2010 has less respect for the culture in addition to the chiefs who push them.\n\n=== Cultural Facts ===\nThe Managaha Island<ref>\"Asian American Pacific Islander National Historic Landmarks Theme Study.\" ''NPS,'' n. d.,\n\nhttps://www.nps.gov/subjects/tellingallamericansstories/upload/0000-Front-Matter.pdf</ref> is sacred in Refaluwasch culture due to the fact Chief Aghurubw is buried there.\n\nRespect in their culture is very important like that of the Chamorro people.\n\nIn the history of their culture there is a concept called tipiyeew. This means solidarity.\n\nMwei-mwei is a Refaluwasch way of adopting children. Its done between family members most of the time. Its initiated by females. This usually done by wives. The children adopted are usually babies but can be nine, ten, or eleven years old. The natural parents must give permission. After permission is given and the child is adopted the parents who take in the child or children in this custom treat them like a natural child in all situations.\n\n=== Dance ===\nThe people have different dances. There is a dance called Bwai which is a Refaluwasch women dance. A certain cases when males dance they wear large leaves around their necks and wear leaves around their heads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jlrolopai/status/990411629736091649|title=The Refaluwasch Mass Dancers' tribute to Tawa, Kil, & all the other warriors that have passed on. pic.twitter.com/bgqs5eBOLc|last=seps \ud83c\udf6d|date=2018-04-28|website=@jlrolopai|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.guampedia.com/carolinians-on-guam/|title=\u00bb Carolinians on Guam|website=guampedia.com|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref> There is also one for men. It was originally for warriors but spread to other men after the people came to the Mariana Islands.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n808aglDuBEC&q=carolinian#v=snippet&q=carolinian&f=false|title=Marianas Island Legends: Myth and Magic|last=Flood|first=Bo|date=2001|publisher=Bess Press|isbn=9781573061018}}</ref>\n\n=== Traditional Dress, Art, & Body Art ===\n\n==== Dress ====\nThe Carolinian people had to give up native dress for more modest Western clothing.\n\nWomen in different cases would wear a [https://www.saipantribune.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Refaluwasch-pix1.jpg long skirt]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} up to the bottom of their breasts. \n[[File:Flag of the Northern Mariana Islands.svg|center|thumb|The flower structure in a circle is an example of a mwar-mwar.]]\nThere is a wreath that's still worn call a ''mwar-mwar.'' Its still worn by many of them.\n\n==== Body Art ====\nThe female and males have their own tattoos. The females have tattoos are their lower thighs while the males have tattoos on their lower thighs as well as their upper thighs, buttock(s), arms, back of neck, and lower back.<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Carolinians on Guam|date=2009-10-05|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/3985589850/|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Art ====\nThey had a way of drawing(s).<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Pictograph Sail|date=2009-10-06|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/3988874377/|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Death ===\nWhen a person dies lots of sweet-smelling plants are placed all over the person's body. Flovers and vines are used to do this. The body is rolled up into pandanus mat. At the right time women place the body on the water and move it to the edge of a particular reef. The put weights with the dead person in the current which takes the body out to the ocean.\n\nIn their culture places called Fiirourow used to deal with people who passed. These are ancestral villages and places where the Refaluwasch go to burn the belongings of love ones. The places are located  in the reefs.\n\nSometimes the body is burned and the ashes are 'return' to the ocean. In other cases the skull is put in sacred place. This is done for a spiritual reason.\n\n=== Water ===\nThe [https://sablan.house.gov/press-release/northern-mariana-islands-submerged-lands-bill-approved water] around the Northern Mariana Islands has been integral to these people. They have respect and connection to the sea. In the culture men would go out and get food while women would prepare. The women would scale clean and scale [https://issuu.com/pmri/docs/jmf_issue8_web fish]. \nThey have celestial navigation skills. They share with the Native Hawaiians and Chamorro people a common ancient origin and seafaring navigation achievements.\n[[File:Mau-star-compass.png|thumb|This star compass was made by Mau Piailug. This is part of his Carolinian navigational system.<ref>{{Diff|en:Mau_Piailug|diff=|oldid=872908687|label=en:Mau_Piailug,   oldid 872908687}}{{Circular reference|date=February 2020}}</ref>]]\n\n=== Carolinian customary law ===\nUnder this law [http://studentorgs.kentlaw.iit.edu/jicl/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/01/Ristroph_customary_nmi.pdf property] can be owned by one person or a whole family. The CNMI Code says family land should be held for the equal enjoyment of all members.\n\nTraditional Carolinian land tenure involve women. Land was passed down from mother to daughter. The land was owned and controlled by women. The oldest female in the maternal line with the longest held title would be a \"trustee\" for the rest of the lineage members.\n\n==Food==\nSubsistence agriculture to get food was how these people lived from 1815\u20131914 in the CNMI.<ref>{{Citation|last=Johnson|first=Bruce|chapter=http://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/p27481/pdf/ch0910.pdf|date=November 2007|publisher=ANU Press|isbn=9781921313479|doi=10.22459/tlam.11.2007.09|title=Talking and Listening in the Age of Modernity: Essays on the history of sound}}</ref>\n\nSeafood makes up a big part of their meat dishes. They have a history of fishing that goes over thousands of years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wpcouncil.org/managed-fishery-ecosystems/mariana-archipelago/|title=Mariana Archipelago|website=wpcouncil.org|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref> Fishing trips are not just for feeding a small group of people but also for annual village parties, baptisms and confirmations, marriages, and other special celebrations. After fish are caught some of it may be given to the wife of the fisherman's family members as well as others.\n\nIn the past palu (navigators) brought food from the sea. They were respected.\n\nPay\u00far is a fish that is caught using a poiu (fishing stone). Pay\u00far is Refaluwasch for mackerel scad. Poiu consists of a limestone spherical sinker. Its smoothed into the shape of an egg. Holes are put into it. After this an inverted half coconut shell that's either the same size or a little smaller is connected with a cordage. Half of the coconut is filled with mashed  or ground meat from a young coconut. This is similar to churn. This is to draw fish to it. This whole device is tied using a longer cord that's 50 or 60 feet in length. The cord is very long so that the poiu can be lowered into deeper water to feed fish. The poiu is set down on the sea bed before being moved closer to above the water over the course of a month. The Pay\u00far are eventually gathered using a scoop net after getting to the surface.\n\nOne of the ways they prepare food involves using an uumw. Uumw is a traditional underground oven where you roasted food.\n\n==Language==\nThis is a Chuukic language. The language has different versions. Carolinian is one of the official languages in the CNMI.\n\nWritten records of this language go back to the late 1700s.\n\nFor more information read the [[Carolinian language|Carolinian language article]].\n\n==Religion==\n\n=== Traditional religion(s) ===\nDespite the Catholic faith many of them use land to talk to their ancestors. Land in their culture is not just \"property.\" Its a spiritual matter. The place is where people can talk to their ancestors as well as collect unique properties for healing and teach traditions  to future generations.\n\nIn their religion or religions they had i animas. Spiritual ancestors of the CNMI.\n\nThe ocean to these people is not just important to them its spiritual. According to some of them its spiritually central to Carolinian Indigeneity.\n\nBefore the Spanish brought Catholicism there was a religion where Supreme being called Yalafar was worshiped. There is also in this same religion an individual called Can who is a bad spirit.\n\nAfter an individual dies in certain cases their skull is kept because some believe the spirit of the late relative can visit their family when necessary. The living have great respect for the dead. In their culture concerning their traditional religion(s) spirits of the dead can assist or hurt the living. It is also believed that since the spirit world is the source of all things in this world everything that lives or is real must be respected. They contain spirits which go by different names such as ghosts, ''taotaomo'na,'' white ladies, among other names.\n\nAs mentioned earlier they had a system called sawei. They would bring materials (offerings) to their \"fathers\" in exchange for \"spiritual protection.\" One of the other reasons why people brought offerings was because of Yapese magicians. They were believed to have power over the weather.\n\nThe stick dance has a religious origin in Chuuk. It is claimed that a spirit taught this centuries ago during a war between two clans. The dance started of as a way of fighting.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Roman Catholicism ===\n[[File:Saipan Mount Carmel Cathedral.JPG|thumb|This is an entrance to the Our Lady Of Mother Carmel Cathedral Parish. The parish says this place represents the strength of the Carolinian and Chamorro people in terms of family and spirit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rcdck.org/parishes/mount-carmel/|title=OUR LADY OF MOUNT CARMEL CATHEDRAL|date=2016-12-27|website=Roman Catholic Diocese of Chalan Kanoa|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>]]\nRoman Catholicism dominates in their societies. Due to Spanish missionary influence, they also use rosaries and novenas.\n\nEfforts to bring Christianity to these people began with Father Paul Klein during the 1600s. One of the people to bring Catholicism to them was Father Juan Antonio Cantova in the early 1700s.\n\nIn 1819 a group of Carolinians was told to accept Christianity before moving to Saipan. The agreement (which included other things) was authorized by officials in Manila.\n\n==Family, Gender, & Health==\n\n=== Family ===\nIn 1999 domestic violence was said to be widespread.<ref name=\":1\" /> Female are expected to treat male relatives with respect when they are present.\n\nIn their language there is a term called ''nemin''. This endearment term is what the men use when referring to their partners.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Gender ===\nIn this culture there are rigid gender divisions.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWhen a male relative is in the same room a female may make herself lower than him. They may even get down on their hands and knees and crawl to where they have to go.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nUtt (pronounced \"oot\") is a meeting house where men congregate. They would also construct canoes in these places. In Garapan there is Carolinian Utt where you can play different sports. Its also used as a community center.<ref>Division of Coastal Resources Management, Bureau of Environmental and Coastal Quality, Office of the Governor, & Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands. \"Public Shoreline Access Guide for Saipan, Tinian, and Rota.\" ''Division of Coastal Resources Management'', September 2015, https://dcrm.gov.mp/wp-content/uploads/crm/ShorelineAccessGuide20151.pdf</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nThe Managaha Island is not only a sacred place but it has been used to get medicinal plants.<ref>\"Saipan lagoon use management plan.\" ''GovInfo,'' [https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CZIC-gb2231-n95-s25-1985-v-1/html/CZIC-gb2231-n95-s25-1985-v-1.htm https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CZIC-gb2231-n95-s25-1985-v-1/html/CZIC-gb2231-n95-s25-1985-v-1.htm.] Accessed 4 April 2019.</ref>\n\nAccording to the Asia Pacific Journal Public Health diabetes was more common among Carolinians in the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Durand|first=A. M.|last2=Bourne|first2=J.|last3=Tuohey-Mote|first3=D.|last4=Khorram|first4=K. D.|last5=Abraham|first5=I. J.|date=1996-1997|title=Diabetes in the indigenous population of the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands|journal=Asia-Pacific Journal of Public Health|volume=9|pages=28\u201332|issn=1010-5395|pmid=10050196|doi=10.1177/101053959700900106}}</ref> In the community in 1999 they were dealing with drug abuse, alcoholism, and obesity. The main drug was crystal methamphetamine.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe people are at an extremely high risk of getting two kinds of cancer. The two kinds are cervical and breast cancer. According to the Division of Public Health for recording Cervical cancer in 2005 the population for 25-34 year old group 88.9 out of 100,000 gets this cancer. In the 35-44 group it is 49.4 out of every 100,000 for this disease. In the 45-54 its 40 per 100,000.\n\nAn article in Preventing Chronic Disease talked about births among Pacific Islanders in the CNMI. In the CNMI Carolinian mothers have a much higher risk of having a premature births than Chinese mothers. They are also more likely to have babies with macrosomia than Filipino moms. Out of all births from 2007-2014 this group is having the most children at 33.2%. Concerning teenage pregnancy its more common among them and other Pacific Islanders than other groups. They also have major issues with obesity and cholesterol. Diabetes is still an issue in their community. CNMI Pacific Islanders more so than other groups are engaging in unhealthy actions such as using tobacco, chewing betel nut, and consuming alcohol.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dela Cruz|first=Rica|last2=Grant|first2=Jeanolivia|last3=Heck|first3=Julia E.|last4=Cash|first4=Haley L.|date=2018-03-08|title=Disparities in Adverse Perinatal Outcomes Among Pacific Islanders in the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands|journal=Preventing Chronic Disease|volume=15|pages=E29|doi=10.5888/pcd15.170385|issn=1545-1151|pmc=5858154|pmid=29522702}}</ref> The chewing of betel nut is contributing to preterm birth rates among this.\n\n==Media==\nThe Refaluwasch have little to no presence in films. Most films have white people in speaking roles. Pacific Islanders in Hollywood according to report from USC only make a fraction of the actors and actresses in film in recent years.<ref>Smith, Stacy L. Choueiti, Mark, et al. \"Inequality in 1,100 Popular Films: Examining Portrayals of Gender, Race/Ethnicity, LGBT & Disability from 2007 to 2017\" http://assets.uscannenberg.org/docs/inequality-in-1100-popular-films.pdf ''USC''</ref>\n\nThey also have little to no presence in television. Pacific Islanders makeup a fraction of the characters on prime time. They makeup just 0.2% of acting roles where the character appears regularly. More than 64% of series as of 2017 did not feature a Pacific Islander or Asian American regularly. Their white counterparts will usually get three times the screen time they get in the same program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-asians-on-television-study-20170913-story.html|title=Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders remain underrepresented on television, study finds|last=Braxton|first=Greg|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\nComic strips in the early 20th century and 19th century had little to no female Refaluwasch whether they be cartoonists or minor characters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/comic-strip|title=Comic strip - Asia and the manga|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n[[Aghurubw|Chief Aghurubw]] (????-????) of the Ghatoliyool clan<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvariety.com/index.php/special-features/my-marianas/56422-managaha-s-cultural-heritage|title=Marianas Variety - Managaha's cultural heritage|website=mvariety.com|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> and chief of Satawal brought the Refaluwasch in Satawal to CNMI in 1815.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pireport.org/articles/2006/09/19/saipan-carolinians-commemorate-great-leader|title=SAIPAN CAROLINIANS COMMEMORATE GREAT LEADER {{!}} Pacific Islands Report|website=pireport.org|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\nChief Nguschul of Elato (a coral reef atoll consisting of three islands) brought his group to what is now CNMI in 1815 and named a village Ppiyal Oolang which in English means \"beach view sky.\"\n\nFormer Mayor Elias Parong Sablan (1900-1968) became second mayor of Saipan in 1945 and served 3 four-year terms until 1957.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/overcoming-the-odds-a-look-at-uncle-daves-new-book/|title=Overcoming the odds: A look at Uncle Dave's new book|date=2015-03-12|website=Saipan News, Headlines, Events, Ads {{!}} Saipan Tribune|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AQePDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=elias+p+sablan+death#v=onepage&q=elias%20parong%20sablan&f=false|title=A Degree of Success through Curiosity: True Story of a Young Boy Eager to Learn and Find His Calling in Life|last=Sablan|first=David M.|date=2017-03-07|publisher=Dorrance Publishing|isbn=9781480937109}}</ref> He was also Judge of Saipan's Community Court, Chairman of Saipan's Board of Education, Chief of Police, and member of Congress (Saipan's). The man also owned a grocery store.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1955/09/03/saipans-sablan|title=Saipan's Sablan|last=Hellman|first=Geoffrey T.|date=1955-08-27|access-date=2019-05-16|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n[[File:Mau Piailug.gif|thumb|Picture of Piailug in his latter years.]]\n[[Mau Piailug]] (1932-2010) was a master navigator involve in using non-instrument wayfinding.\n\nLarry Saralu was one of the most famous singers in the early Post World War II years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/guampedia/docs/recent_history|title=Recent History|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref> He was Saipanese Carolinian.\n\nLino (Urushemeyoung) Mettao Olopai<ref>Taman, Candido B. et al. A House Commemorative Resolution. ''House Of Representatives.'' 2006, http://cnmileg.gov.mp/documents/house/hse_comres/15/HCR15-17.pdf</ref> (1940-) was responsible for maintaining the Carolinian culture.\n\nBenigno Repeki Fitial (1945-) became the first Carolinian governor of CNMI in 2006 and served until 2013. During this time he was a member of the U. S. Republican Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://classic.nga.org/cms/benigno-fitial|title=Ben\u00edgno Fitial|website=classic.nga.org|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref>\n\nCandy Taman (1948- ) is a Chamorro-Carolinian recording artist who made Chamorro and Carolinian music. He formed a band called Local Breed with Frank \"Bokonggo\" Pangelinan. He would later rename it Tropocisette. He pioneered Chamorro music on CNMI.\n\nThe first Refaluwasch woman to become a lawyer was Jacinta (Cinta) Matagolai<ref>Black, P. Other People's Nostalgia, Other People's Pride. ''The Contemporary Pacific,'' 2000. Accessed 26-03-2019.</ref> Kaipat.\n\nJoseph James Norita Camacho became the first Carolinian judge in CNMI.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/bda46235-1dfb-11e4-aedf-250bc8c9958e/|title=Camacho takes his oath in Carolinian\u2014a first|date=2011-11-18|website=Saipan News, Headlines, Events, Ads {{!}} Saipan Tribune|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> He became a judge in 2011.\n\nSarilyn Ogumoro Escobar became the first Carolinian to be a commissioned [http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/49801-first-carolinian-to-be-a-commissioned-officer-in-us-navy.php officer] in US Navy.<ref>Press Release. \"First Carolinian to be a commissioned officer in US Navy\" ''Marianas Variety.'' 2012, http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/49801-first-carolinian-to-be-a-commissioned-officer-in-us-navy.php</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Allen, Stewart D. & Amesbury, Judith R. Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands As a Fishing Community. ''NOAA''.  2012, https://www.pifsc.noaa.gov/library/pubs/tech/NOAA_Tech_Memo_PIFSC_36.pdf\n*Bagnol, Raquel C. Managaha's cultural heritage. ''Marianas Variety''. 2013, http://www.mvariety.com/index.php/special-features/my-marianas/56422-managaha-s-cultural-heritage\n*Carrell, Toni L. Micronesia Submerged Cultural Resources Assessment. ''NPS.'' 1991'',''https://www.nps.gov/orgs/1635/upload/NNPS_903_D161_-37387.pdf\n*Collier, R. Navigating Modernity / The Carolinians, a tiny group of islanders on Saipan, in the western Pacific, have seen their ancient culture succumb to consumerism. As they try to salvage what they can of their past, they are helping to lead a cultural revival am. ''SF Gate.''1999, https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Navigating-Modernity-The-Carolinians-a-tiny-3774200.php\n*\"Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands.\" ''Department of the Interior,'' https://www.doi.gov/oia/islands/cnmi<nowiki/>Accessed 3 April 2019.\n*James Ellis, S. Saipan Carolinian, One Chuukic Language Blended From Many. ''University Of Hawaii''. 2012, http://www.ling.hawaii.edu/graduate/Dissertations/JimEllisFinal.pdf\n*Encinares, Erwin. Tudela: Indigenous Affairs Expo a success. ''Saipan Tribune.'' 2018, https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/tudela-indigenous-affairs-expo-a-success/\n*Frain, Sylvia C. 'Make America Secure'. ''Pacific Media Centre.'' 2018, https://ojs.aut.ac.nz/pacific-journalism-review/article/download/407/629/\n*Lirio, Lori Lyn C. 2nd Indigenous Cultural Expo bigger than last year's. ''Marianas Variety.'' 2018, http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/108113-2nd-indigenous-cultural-expo-bigger-than-last-year-s\n*Manabat, B. Flame Tree Arts Festival honors 11 artists, cultural advocates. ''Marianas Variety.'' 2016, http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/85452-flame-tree-arts-festival-honors-11-artists-cultural-advocates\n*Severance, Craig. Customary Exchange Maintains Cultural Continuity. ''Pacific Islands Fishery News.'' 2010, https://www.wpcouncil.org/outreach/newsletters/PIFN_summer2010.pdf\n*CNMI Supreme Court. In The Matter Of The Estate of Aguida Amires. ''Supreme Court CNMI''. 1996, http://www.cnmilaw.org/pdf/supreme/1997-MP-08.pdf\n*Taman, Candido B. et al. A House Commemorative Resolution. ''House Of Representatives.'' 2006, http://cnmileg.gov.mp/documents/house/hse_comres/15/HCR15-17.pdf\n*{{cite web |title=Joshua Project Carolinian of Northern Mariana Islands Ethnic People Prolife | url=http://www.joshuaproject.net/peopctry.php?rog3=CQ&rop3=101890 | accessdate=December 1, 2008 }}\n*{{cite web |title=Saipan History & Culture |url=http://www.castleresorts.com/Home/vacation/micronesia/saipan?sid=50 |accessdate=December 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006172844/http://www.castleresorts.com/Home/vacation/micronesia/saipan?sid=50 |archivedate=October 6, 2008 }}\n*{{cite web|title=NEA National Heritage Fellowships: Felipe I. and Joseph K. Ruak, Carolinian stick dancers |url=http://www.nea.gov/honors/heritage/fellows/fellow.php?id=2003_08 |accessdate=December 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005134438/http://www.nea.gov///honors/heritage/fellows/fellow.php?id=2003_08 |archivedate=October 5, 2008 }}\n*[http://www.theinsularempire.com ''\"The Insular Empire: America in the Mariana Islands\"''], a one-hour PBS documentary distributed by [http://www.newday.com/films/theinsularempire.html New Day Films]. Directed by Vanessa Warheit. New Day Films, 2010.\n*{{cite web |title=Pacific Footsteps Program Four | url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/arts/radioeye/features/pacificfootsteps/program4.htm | accessdate=December 1, 2008 }}\n*{{cite web|title=CNMI Tanapag --Onwards:People |url=http://www.pacificworlds.com/cnmi/onwards/newfolk.cfm |accessdate=December 3, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006040801/http://www.pacificworlds.com/cnmi/onwards/newfolk.cfm |archivedate=October 6, 2008 }}\n*Goetzfridt, Nicholas J. \"Carolinians on Guam\". ''Guampedia.'' n.d., https://www.guampedia.com/carolinians-on-guam/ Retrieved on March 11, 2019.\n*Lirio, Lori Lyn C. \"September proclaimed Chamorro and Carolinian Cultural Heritage Month\". ''The Guam Daily Post''. 2018, https://www.postguam.com/news/cnmi/september-proclaimed-chamorro-and-carolinian-cultural-heritage-month/article_bc820b5e-aff9-11e8-970b-f3ce9c49a4fc.html Retrieved on March 11, 2019.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carolinian People}}\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Federated States of Micronesia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Northern Mariana Islands]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples of Micronesia]]\n[[Category:Northern Mariana Islands people of Carolinian descent]]\n[[Category:Micronesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expert needed|Ethnic groups|talk=Accuracy Dispute and Expert Needed|reason=Badly written and claimed to be a matriarchal society while having no source. It can even claimed it is a patriarchal society.|date=October 2019}}\n{{Disputed|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{infobox ethnic group\n| group = Carolinians\n| image = Carolinian people in 1915.jpg\n| caption = Carolinian family in 1915\n| population = Over 8,500\n| popplace = [[Saipan]], [[Northern Mariana Islands]], [[Caroline Islands]], [[Guam]]\n| langs = [[Carolinian language|Carolinian]], [[Chamorro language|Chamorro]], [[English language|American English]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| rels = [[Roman Catholic]] & [[Traditional religion]]s|\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| related_groups = \n}}\n\nThe '''Carolinian''', or '''''Refaluwasch''''' (Pronounced ''Ri-fa-lu-wash'') '''people''' are an [[Austronesian people|Austronesian]] ethnic group who originated in [[Oceania]], in the eastern [[Caroline Islands]], with a total population of around 8,500 people. They are also known as '''''Remathau''''' (Pronounced ''Ray-ma-thow'')<ref>{{Citation|last=Pacific Students Media|title=Remathau Graduation 2015|date=2015-06-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aOHbcGPaSso&t=129s|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> in the Yap's outer islands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/articles/aapi-theme-study-essay-12-pacific-islander-heritage.htm|title=Essay 12: Pacific Islanders in the US and their Heritage: Making Visible the Visibly Absent (U.S. National Park Service)|website=nps.gov|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref><ref>Falanruw. Marjorie V. C. & Ruegorang, Francis. Dynamics Of An Island Agroecosystem Where to Now? ''U. S. Forest Service'', n. d. https://www.fs.fed.us/psw/publications/falanruw/psw_2015_falanruw001.pdf</ref> The Carolinian word means \"People of the Deep Sea.\" It is thought that their ancestors may have originally immigrated from [[Asia]] and [[Indonesia]] to [[Micronesia]] around 2,000 years ago. Their primary language is [[Carolinian language|Carolinian]], called ''Refaluwasch'' by native speakers, which has a total of about 5,700 speakers. The Carolinians have a [[matriarchy|matriarchal]] society in which respect is a very important factor in their daily lives, especially toward the [[matriarch]]s. Most Carolinians are of the [[Roman Catholic]] faith.\n\nThe immigration of Carolinians to [[Saipan]] began in the early 19th century, after the [[Spain|Spanish]] killed most of the local population of [[Chamorro people|Chamorro]] natives, reducing them to just 3,700. They began immigrating by sailing mostly from small [[canoe]]s via islands which were previously devastated by a [[typhoon]]. The Carolinians have a much darker complexion than the native [[Chamorro people|Chamorros]].\n\n== Genetics ==\nCarolinians from Saipan have the same lineages with Remathau on the outer islands of Yap.\n\nSome of the people on the islands are Chamolinians which are a mixture of Chamorro and Carolinian heritage.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=VILAR|first=MIGUEL G.|last2=CHAN|first2=CHIM W|last3=SANTOS|first3=DANA R|last4=LYNCH|first4=DANIEL|last5=SPATHIS|first5=RITA|last6=GARRUTO|first6=RALPH M|last7=LUM|first7=J KOJI|date=2013|title=The Origins and Genetic Distinctiveness of the Chamorros of the Marianas Islands: An mtDNA Perspective|journal=American Journal of Human Biology|volume=25|issue=1|pages=116\u2013122|doi=10.1002/ajhb.22349|issn=1042-0533|pmc=4335639|pmid=23180676}}</ref>\n\nThe Carolinians in the CNMI have a high rate of macrosomia which is where the infant is born abnormally large.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/fetal-macrosomia/symptoms-causes/syc-20372579|title=Fetal macrosomia - Symptoms and causes|website=Mayo Clinic|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe people have a long history from Caroline Islands and CNMI too the present in the 21st century.\n\n=== Pre-Spanish era (antiquity-1697) ===\n[[File:Caroline Islands-map.gif|thumb|The islands were the Refaluwasch came from were over 400 miles from what is now the CNMI.]]\nThey have a history stretching back over 3000 years. The Carolinian people had contact with the Chamorro people for years. They had a long history of traveling from the Caroline Islands to what is now Guam. \"Pre-contact\" Carolinian designed pestles, hooks for fishing, and rings made out of shells found on the ground and beneath it show contact between the two groups.\n\nThey built canoes that would have a small roof. The roof only went over less than have of the canoe. The sides could be different colors. The boat could fit over 9 adults in it.<ref>Todino, Junhan B. \"Carolinian Affairs Office float leads parade competition\" ''The Guam Daily Post,''https://www.postguam.com/news/cnmi/carolinian-affairs-office-float-leads-parade-competition/article_ac0f5916-8e43-11e8-a718-d78243d7dab8.html</ref>\n\nCenturies ago they used sea-lanes based off memorize information from the prior generation.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FJ9ULYwX3zgC&pg=PA447&lpg=PA447&dq=chamolinian&source=bl&ots=3g4nRr0x2x&sig=ACfU3U0I-JCe7P6G6wAi3IEbblG_y3DRGA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiszIaU6aviAhVFRKwKHYLOCB84KBDoATAEegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=carolinian&f=false|title=The Cambridge History of the Pacific Islanders|last=Meleisea|first=Malama|last2=Linnekin|first2=Jocelyn|date=2004-03-25|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521003544|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBefore colonial times a system called sawei was practiced. The word sawei means Yapese chief, conqueror, tyrant. This involved the Carolinians gathering once every two or three years in Yap. This system may have existed before the year 1600. More on this is discuss in the religion section.\n\nTrade between the two groups went on even during the Spanish occupation of Guam.\n\n=== Typhoon devastation & Spanish era (1697-1899) ===\nIn the late 1600s leprosy was present in the Marianas. The Spaniards tried to deal with this by quarantining lepers to Saipan and Tinian. These islands were isolated. Spaniards brought Carolinians to these islands to help the hospitals holding the patients with leprosy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uog.edu/uogpress/publications/marc/lepers-in-the-mariana-islands-during-the-spanish-administration-1668-1898-addenda.php|title=Lepers in the Mariana Islands During the Spanish Administration 1668-1898 & Addenda (1899-1949)|website=uog.edu|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\nChamorro sargento mayor Lu\u00eds de Torres became an important source for people who wanted information of the Carolinian people.\n\nDuring this time the people built a boat called Waa (canoe). This is a boat built for the sea. They were for transporting cargo and passengers over long distances.<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Waa (Canoe) of the Caroline Islands|date=2009-10-13|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/4010603376/|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>\n\nIn Guam, Carolinians came to Talofofo Bay in 1788. They were on a voyage. The reason why they stopped there was because they wanted iron. This kind of trade hadn't occurred in over a hundred years in Guam since the military conflicts between Spanish and Chamorros.\n[[File:Talofofo Bay (17420120219).jpg|thumb|This is what Talofofo Bay looks like.]]\nIn the 19th century the Refaluwasch moved from Elato and Satawal islands in the East and West part of the Carolinian islands<ref>Ristroph, Elizabeth Barrett. \"The Survival Of Customary Law In The Northern Mariana Islands.\" ''Chicago-Kent School of Law Illinois Institute of Technology.'' 2007 http://studentorgs.kentlaw.iit.edu/jicl/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/01/Ristroph_customary_nmi.pdf</ref> to what is now Northern Mariana Islands.<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Talofofo Bay|date=2009-10-06|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/3986693874/|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>   \n[[File:Elato Lamolior Landsat.jpg|left|thumb|This is an image of Elato from outer space.]]\n[[File:Micro Beach (530316786).jpg|left|thumb|This beach is where the two chiefs came. Aghurubw loved this place.]]\nThe two islands were destroyed by typhoon. Refaluwasch were starving during this time. Chief Nguschul of Elato along with Chief Aghurubw of Satawal led the people to the NMI. They landed at Micro Beach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/editorials/61221-refaluwasch-come-to-saipan|title=BC's Tales of the Pacific: Refaluwasch come to Saipan|last=Variety|first=Marianas|website=Marianas Variety|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref> After coming to Saipan they built a village called Arabwal.  Right now this area is in American Memorial Park.<ref>\"A Living Legacy.\" ''NPS,''[https://www.nps.gov/amme/planyourvisit/upload/AMME_S2_interactive.pdf https://www.nps.gov/amme/planyourvisit/upload/AMME_S2_interactive.pdf.] Accessed 4 April 2019.</ref> This was not the only village built. The other one Ppiyal Oolang.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=IVVQ46epBqwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=micronesian+legends#v=onepage&q=micronesian%20legends&f=false|title=Micronesian Legends|last=Flood|first=Bo|last2=Strong|first2=Beret E.|last3=Flood|first3=William|date=2002|publisher=Bess Press|isbn=9781573061292}}</ref> This area is where Nguschul and his group settled. The Carolinians continued to come here in the 100s as well as other areas such as Guam and Tinian.<ref name=\":6\">Riesenberg, Saul H. & Kaneshiro, Shiegeru. ''A Caroline Islands Script''. Smithsonian Institution, n. d.  https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/22111/bae_bulletin_173_1960_60_269-333.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y</ref>  \n[[File:Saipan from ISS 2.png|left|thumb|This is an aerial view of Saipan the island the people came too after the islands were hit by the typhoon.]]\nThe Spanish allowed them to keep their culture.\n\nDuring the mid 1800s Carolinians moved to Tamuning due to a 1849 typhoon which devastated their land.<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Carolinians, 1902|date=2009-10-06|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/3985939473/|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time they took over [http://www.soest.hawaii.edu/pfrp/reprints/Amesbury_Terra_Australis39_2013.pdf inter-island] travel during the latter half of the 18th century and 19th century. They used a ship called ''banca'' to travel.\n\nIn 1865 265 Carolinians were transferred from the Carolines by Englishman George Johnston. He moved them to Pagan.<ref name=\":2\">Amesbury, Judith R. \"What are all those people doing in that ecosystem?\" Scientific and Statistical Committee Western Pacific Fishery Management Council, NOAA, n. d.https://www.pifsc.noaa.gov/media/news/mariana_archipelago_ecosystem_science_implementation_plan_workshop_amesbury.pdf</ref>\n\nThe Tanapag village was setup by some Refaluwasch who left Tinian island in 1879.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nTen years later in 1889 Governor Olive had the Refaluwasch on Tinian relocate to Tanapag.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== German period (1899-1914) ===\nSpain sold the Northern Mariana Islands to Germany in 1899, after losing Guam to the United States in 1898. This area became known as the German Northern Marianas. This was the shortest period a country controlled this area. They didn't change the culture of the Carolinians a lot but did bring in new ways of schooling, bureaucracy, architecture, and administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guampedia.com/pop-cultures-cnmi/|title=\u00bb POP Cultures: CNMI|website=guampedia.com|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref> The legal system was transparent towards both Carolinians and Chamorros.\n\nGeorg Fritz on November 17, 1899 became the first district officer of this area. He set up programs which brought the Carolinians and Chamorro people living on the islands together.\n\nMarriages between German settlers or colonial officers and Carolinians at Saipan occurred. The marriage did not allow for citizenship for either the Carolinian partner or children. This was the same for Chamorro people.\n\nCarolinians were peaceful towards the Germans.\n\nThe population measurement in 1901 for these individuals are 772. The last population count the Germans did in 1914 recorded 1,109 of them.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arif|first=Sigit Supadmo|last2=Prabowo|first2=Abi|last3=Suprapto|first3=Anjar|last4=Kurniawan|first4=Judy|date=2007-03-01|title=Irrigation asset management plan: concept development and its implementation in Indonesia|journal=Jurnal Keteknikan Pertanian|volume=21|pages=45\u201356|doi=10.19028/jtep.21.1.45-56|issn=0216-3365}}</ref>\n\nCarolinians didn't own land during this time unlike the Chamorros living here.\n\n=== US Naval era (1899-1903) ===\n[[File:Richard Leary.jpg|thumb|An image of former Governor Leary.]]\nIn Guam the people were made to adopt Western ways because of the U.S. Naval Administration.\n\nOne example of this was banning [[nudity]]. In Guam the first American governor was [[Richard P. Leary]] (1899-1900). He issued an order where Carolinian women in Guam weren't allowed to be naked when ever he visited. This was done away with by Governor [[William E. Sewell]] (1903-1904). The men were not allowed to be naked either. Many went to Saipan to avoid doing this. The constant nudity of the people bothered the second American governor [[Seaton Schroeder]] (1900-1903) so much that he decided to move them off the island. They were sent to CNMI through an agreement with the Germans who controlled those islands. They wanted additional laborers.\n\n=== Japanese Administration & Occupation (1914-1945) ===\nJapan took over the Mariana Islands in 1914. They were able to keep it due to the [https://www.britannica.com/place/Northern-Mariana-Islands#ref273250 Treaty of Versailles].\n[[File:American Memorial Park.jpg|left|thumb|This is located on Saipan and is the location of Arabwal. The names of Carolinians who died during WWII are inscribed in granite panels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/amme/learn/photosmultimedia/photogallery.htm|title=Photo Gallery - American Memorial Park (U.S. National Park Service)|last=Saipan|first=Mailing Address: P. O. Box 5198|last2=Us|first2=MP 96950 Phone:234-7207 x2002 Contact|website=nps.gov|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/amme/learn/historyculture/upload/Marianas-Memorial-Listing.pdf|title=Marianas Memorial|date=2019-05-15|website=National Park Service|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Chamorro and Kanaka girls in 1930s.jpg|thumb|Under Japan Carolinians in kanakas like the one on the right still practice their culture. The fashion concerning the leaf structures was even present then.|alt=]]\nThe Carolinians had villages which the Japanese called kanakas. These villages were controlled by sosoncho and soncho. Sosoncho is a general village chieftain. A soncho is a village chieftain. These chieftains didn't always have position under the traditional tribal patterns.\n\nWhile the Japanese controlled these islands they used these people as laborers for mining and handling phosphate ore. One of the mines was in Angaur under the Palau group.<ref name=\":6\" /> Carolinians were not treated as well as the Chamorros who worked with them. The Japanese and other colonial powers during this time (WWI-WWII) would not allow Carolinians to do canoe navigation over large distances.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time a term was used to refer to the Micronesian people under Japanese control which was 'Tomin.' Tomin meant inhabitants of the land. The Carolinian and Chamorro people viewed this as a put down since Japanese used it as part of discrimination. The people were kept under strict surveillance.<ref>Guampedia. ''\"Marianas History Conference III - Part 3\"'' issuu''.'' 2018, https://issuu.com/guampedia/docs/mhc_iii_2017_3</ref> They were enslaved in 1944.<ref name=\":0\">Collier, R. Navigating Modernity / The Carolinians, a tiny group of islanders on Saipan, in the western Pacific, have seen their ancient culture succumb to consumerism. As they try to salvage what they can of their past, they are helping to lead a cultural revival am. ''SF Gate.'' 1999, https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Navigating-Modernity-The-Carolinians-a-tiny-3774200.php</ref> During this time few in this indigenous community served as scouts for the U.S. military. They served in the U.S. Marines.\n\nOn Saipan some Refaluwasch families were under an American military government. Some of them were in Camp Susupe. They were in a Chamorro-Carolinian area of the Camp.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=The Northern Mariana Islands Judiciary: A Historical Overview|last=|first=|publisher=Northern Marianas Judiciary Historical Society|year=2011|isbn=978-0-615-42762-1|location=http://www.justice.gov.mp/uploads/History_Book_-_ch1-4.pdf|pages=}}</ref> <gallery>\nFile:Camp susupe sign.JPG|The camp was used for Refaluwasch people as well as Japanese.\n</gallery>Some Refaluwasch were restricted from returning to their lands during this occupation. One of the reasons why they were interned was because the United States government wanted them to learn English as well as American political and social life. They were allowed to farm and fish before the evening. They had to return to the Camp when night came.\n\nOn Saipan during April 1945 there were 810 Refaluwasch on the island. Later in September of that more people of that group were brought into Saipan.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAfter the Japanese surrender Refaluwasch were allowed to [http://www.anthropology.hawaii.edu/people/emeritus/white/NEH_2010/required%20pdfs/Camacho_chap_5_ed_nov24.pdf return]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} to their lands.\n\n=== Post World War II (1945-present) ===\nThe people didn't object to the edicts of the U.S. military authorities. They were thankful for the basic necessities provided by Naval Military Government. The authorities founded a police force consisting of Carolinians and Chamorros for Camp Susupe and Chalan Kanoa. It was called Native Police and was 87 strong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/letters-to-the-editor/54440-a-saipan-marine-died|title=A Saipan Marine died|last=Variety|first=Marianas|website=Marianas Variety|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref>\n\nUnder the Naval Military Government Carolinian families in certain cases adopted orphans of Korean or Japanese descent. They were orphaned because of WWII.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nThey have served in the Vietnam War. Only less than a [https://sablan.house.gov/vietnam-veterans-cnmi-get-congressional-tribute 100] are known.\n\nBefore 2004 the Carolinians and Chamorro people were competing with each other before banding together. This is sometimes called Chamolinian. They did this to challenge what they call outsiders. Outsiders involve Filipinos and Japanese among other groups of immigrants and/or migrants.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FJ9ULYwX3zgC&pg=PA447&lpg=PA447&dq=chamolinian&source=bl&ots=3g4nRr0x2x&sig=ACfU3U0I-JCe7P6G6wAi3IEbblG_y3DRGA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiszIaU6aviAhVFRKwKHYLOCB84KBDoATAEegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=chamolinian&f=false|title=The Cambridge History of the Pacific Islanders|last=Meleisea|first=Malama|date=2004-03-25|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521003544|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018 Refaluwasch in the Marianas have one of the highest rates of service in the U.S. military.\n\nIn 2018 former Acting Governor of Northern Mariana Islands Victor Hocog [https://www.postguam.com/news/cnmi/september-proclaimed-chamorro-and-carolinian-cultural-heritage-month/article_bc820b5e-aff9-11e8-970b-f3ce9c49a4fc.html signed] a proclamation to make September Chamorro and Carolinian Heritage Month. In the month you have special day called Chief Aghurubw Day. The former is held on Sept. 29. Chief Aghurubw and his people travel from Satawal to Saipan before setting up the first Carolinian settlement in CNMI in 1815.\n\n==== Population & Economic Figures ====\nThe population in 1999 on the CNMI was 3,500.\n\nCarolinians due to Compact of Free Association have increased greatly on [https://www.guampedia.com/carolinians-on-guam/ Guam]. As of the 2000 U.S. census the population is around 11,000.\n\nThey are 4.6% of the population on CNMI. According to the 2010 American FactFinder profile on CNMI the Carolinians number over 2,400.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_DPMP_MPDP1&prodType=table|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U. S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|access-date=2019-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106145130/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_DPMP_MPDP1&prodType=table|archive-date=2018-11-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Saipan they are 20% of the population.<ref name=\":4\">Guampedia. Chamorro Cultural Values Workshop-Summary Workshop Report. ''Guampedia, 2016,'' http://www.guampedia.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Chamorro_Cultural_Values_Workshop.pdf</ref> The population in the United States has increased a lot.<ref>Hixson, Lindsay, Hepler, Bradford B. & Kim, Myoung O. The Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Population: 2010. ''Census,'' May 2012, https://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/briefs/c2010br-12.pdf</ref> Outside the CNMI and Guam in the United States Washington State has the biggest population of them.<ref name=\":5\">EPIC & Asian Americans Advancing Justice. Native Hawaiians & Pacific Islanders A Community Of Contrasts 2014 In The United States. ''Empower PDI,'' 2014, https://www.empoweredpi.org/uploads/1/1/4/1/114188135/a_community_of_contrasts_nhpi_us_2014-1.pdf</ref> The population in the state is 127. In Seattle there is 116 of them.<ref name=\":5\" /> Concerning age 40% of the people in this group are less than 18 while only 2% of this group are over 65.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nDuring the late 90's it was estimated they had 20 percent unemployment. Also during this time they were behind the Chamorros in terms of economics. The Chamorro people were more economical development than they were. This has been going on for a long time in their community. They were susceptible to progress' bad effects.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Navigating-Modernity-The-Carolinians-a-tiny-3774200.php|title=Navigating Modernity / The Carolinians, a tiny group of islanders on Saipan, in the western Pacific, have seen their ancient culture succumb to consumerism. As they try to salvage what they can of their past, they are helping to lead a cultural revival am - SFChronicle.com|date=1999-03-07|website=sfgate.com|access-date=2019-04-15}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2010 U.S. Census the people along with other Micronesian groups have lower home owner ship than the many other ethnic groups in the country. They are mainly renters.<ref name=\":5\" /> Their household sizes are 3.9. They have bigger household sizes than Latinos. Only 14% of them are homeowners while the rest are renters.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThey make up 2% of the population in Palau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/ps.html|title=Australia - Oceania :: Palau \u2014 The World Factbook - Central Intelligence Agency|website=cia.gov|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Metzgar|first=Eric|date=November 2016|title=Carolinian Voyaging In The New Millennium|url=http://marshall.csu.edu.au/MJHSS/Issue2006/MJHSS2006_117.pdf|journal=Micronesian Journal of the Humanities and Social Sciences|volume=5|pages=293\u2013305|via=}}</ref>\n\n==== Resistance to U.S. militarization ====\nDespite the fact there are high rates of service for the military in this community there has been resistance to buildup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://csudh.kanopy.com/welcome/video/insular-empire-america-mariana-islands|title=Welcome to California State University Dominguez Hills {{!}} Kanopy|website=csudh.kanopy.com|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/guampedia/docs/0608-fanohge_famalao_an|title=Fanohge Famal\u00e5o'an & Fan'tachu Fama'lauan|website=Issuu|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> Refaluwasch women are using different ways to resist military buildup in the Marianas Archipelago. They have used digital, legal, political, and spiritual methods to resist this. They are using lawsuits supported by the National Environmental Protection Act. They are using this against the Department of Defense (DoD) and Department of the Navy.\n\n== Politics ==\n[[File:Benigno Fitial and Josie Fitial.jpg|thumb|A picture of the former governor Fitial and his wife Josie Fitial.]]\nThere has been efforts to bring the Marianas together. In the 1960s people submitted a resolution against putting the Marianas under one government. The Carolinians in the Northern Marianas desired stronger ties with Refaluwasch abroad in Micronesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guampedia.com/history-of-efforts-to-reunify-the-mariana-islands/|title=\u00bb History of Efforts to Reunify the Mariana Islands|website=guampedia.com|access-date=2019-05-16}}</ref> A lot of them wanted CNMI to be freely associated with the U. S.\n\nThe population is represented in the legislature however the Chamorro people are dominant in politics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Northern-Mariana-Islands|title=Northern Mariana Islands {{!}} history - geography|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\nElias Parung Sablan became Mayor of Saipan in 1945.\n\n[[Benigno Fitial|Benigno R. Fitial]] (1945- ) became the CNMI's first governor of Carolinian descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/58540-refaluwasch-gather-to-express-support-for-heinz|title=Refaluwasch gather to express support for Heinz|last=Variety|first=Marianas|website=Marianas Variety|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n[[File:Timothy Villagomez.jpg|thumb|Picture of Villagomez.]]\nLieutenant Governor [[Timothy Villagomez|Timothy P. Villagomez]] served under Fitial.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mycnmi.blogspot.com/2007/04/1st-ever-carolinian-language-symposium.html|title=.: 1st Ever Carolinian Language Symposium April 18 & 19, 2007|last=Blogger|first=Cnmi|date=2007-04-18|website=.|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/tim-villagomez-okd-to-travel-to-ph/|title=Tim Villagomez OK'd to travel to PH|date=2018-11-18|website=Saipan News, Headlines, Events, Ads {{!}} Saipan Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>\n\nCinta Kaipat served in CNMI House of Representatives in the 15th CNMI Legislature.\n\n[[Joe Camacho|Joseph James Norita Camacho]] was a member of 16th CNMI House of Representatives and held the position as House Floor Leader. He was elected to this position in 2007.\n\nIn the Obama Administration a Refaluwasch women named Rellani Bennett Ogumoro served as the Policy Advisor for the Domestic Policy Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@ObamaWhiteHouse/indigenous-peoples-voices-from-the-white-house-fe22d7eb2b2f|title=Indigenous Peoples: Voices from the White House|last=House|first=The Obama White|date=2016-09-26|website=Medium|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apps.law.asu.edu/apps/directory/?Letter=O|title=Sandra Day O'Connor College of Law|website=apps.law.asu.edu|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref><ref>Navigating a Political Relationship: Indigenous and American in the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands. ''Arizona State University'', n. d. https://asuevents.asu.edu/sites/default/files/rellaniogumoroll3.pdf</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Managaha SW 2014.JPG|thumb|View of a portion of Managaha Island.]]\nTheir culture originated from the islands Yap and Chuuk in what is now the Federated States of Micronesia. The present day generation as of 2010 has less respect for the culture in addition to the chiefs who push them.\n\n=== Cultural Facts ===\nThe Managaha Island<ref>\"Asian American Pacific Islander National Historic Landmarks Theme Study.\" ''NPS,'' n. d.,\n\nhttps://www.nps.gov/subjects/tellingallamericansstories/upload/0000-Front-Matter.pdf</ref> is sacred in Refaluwasch culture due to the fact Chief Aghurubw is buried there.\n\nRespect in their culture is very important like that of the Chamorro people.\n\nIn the history of their culture there is a concept called tipiyeew. This means solidarity.\n\nMwei-mwei is a Refaluwasch way of adopting children. Its done between family members most of the time. Its initiated by females. This usually done by wives. The children adopted are usually babies but can be nine, ten, or eleven years old. The natural parents must give permission. After permission is given and the child is adopted the parents who take in the child or children in this custom treat them like a natural child in all situations.\n\n=== Dance ===\nThe people have different dances. There is a dance called Bwai which is a Refaluwasch women dance. A certain cases when males dance they wear large leaves around their necks and wear leaves around their heads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jlrolopai/status/990411629736091649|title=The Refaluwasch Mass Dancers' tribute to Tawa, Kil, & all the other warriors that have passed on. pic.twitter.com/bgqs5eBOLc|last=seps \ud83c\udf6d|date=2018-04-28|website=@jlrolopai|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.guampedia.com/carolinians-on-guam/|title=\u00bb Carolinians on Guam|website=guampedia.com|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref> There is also one for men. It was originally for warriors but spread to other men after the people came to the Mariana Islands.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n808aglDuBEC&q=carolinian#v=snippet&q=carolinian&f=false|title=Marianas Island Legends: Myth and Magic|last=Flood|first=Bo|date=2001|publisher=Bess Press|isbn=9781573061018}}</ref>\n\n=== Traditional Dress, Art, & Body Art ===\n\n==== Dress ====\nThe Carolinian people had to give up native dress for more modest Western clothing.\n\nWomen in different cases would wear a [https://www.saipantribune.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Refaluwasch-pix1.jpg long skirt]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} up to the bottom of their breasts. \n[[File:Flag of the Northern Mariana Islands.svg|center|thumb|The flower structure in a circle is an example of a mwar-mwar.]]\nThere is a wreath that's still worn call a ''mwar-mwar.'' Its still worn by many of them.\n\n==== Body Art ====\nThe female and males have their own tattoos. The females have tattoos are their lower thighs while the males have tattoos on their lower thighs as well as their upper thighs, buttock(s), arms, back of neck, and lower back.<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Carolinians on Guam|date=2009-10-05|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/3985589850/|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Art ====\nThey had a way of drawing(s).<ref>{{Citation|last=Guampedia|title=Pictograph Sail|date=2009-10-06|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guampedia/3988874377/|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Death ===\nWhen a person dies lots of sweet-smelling plants are placed all over the person's body. Flovers and vines are used to do this. The body is rolled up into pandanus mat. At the right time women place the body on the water and move it to the edge of a particular reef. The put weights with the dead person in the current which takes the body out to the ocean.\n\nIn their culture places called Fiirourow used to deal with people who passed. These are ancestral villages and places where the Refaluwasch go to burn the belongings of love ones. The places are located  in the reefs.\n\nSometimes the body is burned and the ashes are 'return' to the ocean. In other cases the skull is put in sacred place. This is done for a spiritual reason.\n\n=== Water ===\nThe [https://sablan.house.gov/press-release/northern-mariana-islands-submerged-lands-bill-approved water] around the Northern Mariana Islands has been integral to these people. They have respect and connection to the sea. In the culture men would go out and get food while women would prepare. The women would scale clean and scale [https://issuu.com/pmri/docs/jmf_issue8_web fish]. \nThey have celestial navigation skills. They share with the Native Hawaiians and Chamorro people a common ancient origin and seafaring navigation achievements.\n[[File:Mau-star-compass.png|thumb|This star compass was made by Mau Piailug. This is part of his Carolinian navigational system.<ref>{{Diff|en:Mau_Piailug|diff=|oldid=872908687|label=en:Mau_Piailug,   oldid 872908687}}{{Circular reference|date=February 2020}}</ref>]]\n\n=== Carolinian customary law ===\nUnder this law [http://studentorgs.kentlaw.iit.edu/jicl/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/01/Ristroph_customary_nmi.pdf property] can be owned by one person or a whole family. The CNMI Code says family land should be held for the equal enjoyment of all members.\n\nTraditional Carolinian land tenure involve women. Land was passed down from mother to daughter. The land was owned and controlled by women. The oldest female in the maternal line with the longest held title would be a \"trustee\" for the rest of the lineage members.\n\n==Food==\nSubsistence agriculture to get food was how these people lived from 1815\u20131914 in the CNMI.<ref>{{Citation|last=Johnson|first=Bruce|chapter=http://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/p27481/pdf/ch0910.pdf|date=November 2007|publisher=ANU Press|isbn=9781921313479|doi=10.22459/tlam.11.2007.09|title=Talking and Listening in the Age of Modernity: Essays on the history of sound}}</ref>\n\nSeafood makes up a big part of their meat dishes. They have a history of fishing that goes over thousands of years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wpcouncil.org/managed-fishery-ecosystems/mariana-archipelago/|title=Mariana Archipelago|website=wpcouncil.org|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref> Fishing trips are not just for feeding a small group of people but also for annual village parties, baptisms and confirmations, marriages, and other special celebrations. After fish are caught some of it may be given to the wife of the fisherman's family members as well as others.\n\nIn the past palu (navigators) brought food from the sea. They were respected.\n\nPay\u00far is a fish that is caught using a poiu (fishing stone). Pay\u00far is Refaluwasch for mackerel scad. Poiu consists of a limestone spherical sinker. Its smoothed into the shape of an egg. Holes are put into it. After this an inverted half coconut shell that's either the same size or a little smaller is connected with a cordage. Half of the coconut is filled with mashed  or ground meat from a young coconut. This is similar to churn. This is to draw fish to it. This whole device is tied using a longer cord that's 50 or 60 feet in length. The cord is very long so that the poiu can be lowered into deeper water to feed fish. The poiu is set down on the sea bed before being moved closer to above the water over the course of a month. The Pay\u00far are eventually gathered using a scoop net after getting to the surface.\n\nOne of the ways they prepare food involves using an uumw. Uumw is a traditional underground oven where you roasted food.\n\n==Language==\nThis is a Chuukic language. The language has different versions. Carolinian is one of the official languages in the CNMI.\n\nWritten records of this language go back to the late 1700s.\n\nFor more information read the [[Carolinian language|Carolinian language article]].\n\n==Religion==\n\n=== Traditional religion(s) ===\nDespite the Catholic faith many of them use land to talk to their ancestors. Land in their culture is not just \"property.\" Its a spiritual matter. The place is where people can talk to their ancestors as well as collect unique properties for healing and teach traditions  to future generations.\n\nIn their religion or religions they had i animas. Spiritual ancestors of the CNMI.\n\nThe ocean to these people is not just important to them its spiritual. According to some of them its spiritually central to Carolinian Indigeneity.\n\nBefore the Spanish brought Catholicism there was a religion where Supreme being called Yalafar was worshiped. There is also in this same religion an individual called Can who is a bad spirit.\n\nAfter an individual dies in certain cases their skull is kept because some believe the spirit of the late relative can visit their family when necessary. The living have great respect for the dead. In their culture concerning their traditional religion(s) spirits of the dead can assist or hurt the living. It is also believed that since the spirit world is the source of all things in this world everything that lives or is real must be respected. They contain spirits which go by different names such as ghosts, ''taotaomo'na,'' white ladies, among other names.\n\nAs mentioned earlier they had a system called sawei. They would bring materials (offerings) to their \"fathers\" in exchange for \"spiritual protection.\" One of the other reasons why people brought offerings was because of Yapese magicians. They were believed to have power over the weather.\n\nThe stick dance has a religious origin in Chuuk. It is claimed that a spirit taught this centuries ago during a war between two clans. The dance started of as a way of fighting.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Roman Catholicism ===\n[[File:Saipan Mount Carmel Cathedral.JPG|thumb|This is an entrance to the Our Lady Of Mother Carmel Cathedral Parish. The parish says this place represents the strength of the Carolinian and Chamorro people in terms of family and spirit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rcdck.org/parishes/mount-carmel/|title=OUR LADY OF MOUNT CARMEL CATHEDRAL|date=2016-12-27|website=Roman Catholic Diocese of Chalan Kanoa|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>]]\nRoman Catholicism dominates in their societies. Due to Spanish missionary influence, they also use rosaries and novenas.\n\nEfforts to bring Christianity to these people began with Father Paul Klein during the 1600s. One of the people to bring Catholicism to them was Father Juan Antonio Cantova in the early 1700s.\n\nIn 1819 a group of Carolinians was told to accept Christianity before moving to Saipan. The agreement (which included other things) was authorized by officials in Manila.\n\n==Family, Gender, & Health==\n\n=== Family ===\nIn 1999 domestic violence was said to be widespread.<ref name=\":1\" /> Female are expected to treat male relatives with respect when they are present.\n\nIn their language there is a term called ''nemin''. This endearment term is what the men use when referring to their partners.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Gender ===\nIn this culture there are rigid gender divisions.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWhen a male relative is in the same room a female may make herself lower than him. They may even get down on their hands and knees and crawl to where they have to go.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nUtt (pronounced \"oot\") is a meeting house where men congregate. They would also construct canoes in these places. In Garapan there is Carolinian Utt where you can play different sports. Its also used as a community center.<ref>Division of Coastal Resources Management, Bureau of Environmental and Coastal Quality, Office of the Governor, & Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands. \"Public Shoreline Access Guide for Saipan, Tinian, and Rota.\" ''Division of Coastal Resources Management'', September 2015, https://dcrm.gov.mp/wp-content/uploads/crm/ShorelineAccessGuide20151.pdf</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nThe Managaha Island is not only a sacred place but it has been used to get medicinal plants.<ref>\"Saipan lagoon use management plan.\" ''GovInfo,'' [https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CZIC-gb2231-n95-s25-1985-v-1/html/CZIC-gb2231-n95-s25-1985-v-1.htm https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CZIC-gb2231-n95-s25-1985-v-1/html/CZIC-gb2231-n95-s25-1985-v-1.htm.] Accessed 4 April 2019.</ref>\n\nAccording to the Asia Pacific Journal Public Health diabetes was more common among Carolinians in the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Durand|first=A. M.|last2=Bourne|first2=J.|last3=Tuohey-Mote|first3=D.|last4=Khorram|first4=K. D.|last5=Abraham|first5=I. J.|date=1996-1997|title=Diabetes in the indigenous population of the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands|journal=Asia-Pacific Journal of Public Health|volume=9|pages=28\u201332|issn=1010-5395|pmid=10050196|doi=10.1177/101053959700900106}}</ref> In the community in 1999 they were dealing with drug abuse, alcoholism, and obesity. The main drug was crystal methamphetamine.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe people are at an extremely high risk of getting two kinds of cancer. The two kinds are cervical and breast cancer. According to the Division of Public Health for recording Cervical cancer in 2005 the population for 25-34 year old group 88.9 out of 100,000 gets this cancer. In the 35-44 group it is 49.4 out of every 100,000 for this disease. In the 45-54 its 40 per 100,000.\n\nAn article in Preventing Chronic Disease talked about births among Pacific Islanders in the CNMI. In the CNMI Carolinian mothers have a much higher risk of having a premature births than Chinese mothers. They are also more likely to have babies with macrosomia than Filipino moms. Out of all births from 2007-2014 this group is having the most children at 33.2%. Concerning teenage pregnancy its more common among them and other Pacific Islanders than other groups. They also have major issues with obesity and cholesterol. Diabetes is still an issue in their community. CNMI Pacific Islanders more so than other groups are engaging in unhealthy actions such as using tobacco, chewing betel nut, and consuming alcohol.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dela Cruz|first=Rica|last2=Grant|first2=Jeanolivia|last3=Heck|first3=Julia E.|last4=Cash|first4=Haley L.|date=2018-03-08|title=Disparities in Adverse Perinatal Outcomes Among Pacific Islanders in the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands|journal=Preventing Chronic Disease|volume=15|pages=E29|doi=10.5888/pcd15.170385|issn=1545-1151|pmc=5858154|pmid=29522702}}</ref> The chewing of betel nut is contributing to preterm birth rates among this.\n\n==Media==\nThe Refaluwasch have little to no presence in films. Most films have white people in speaking roles. Pacific Islanders in Hollywood according to report from USC only make a fraction of the actors and actresses in film in recent years.<ref>Smith, Stacy L. Choueiti, Mark, et al. \"Inequality in 1,100 Popular Films: Examining Portrayals of Gender, Race/Ethnicity, LGBT & Disability from 2007 to 2017\" http://assets.uscannenberg.org/docs/inequality-in-1100-popular-films.pdf ''USC''</ref>\n\nThey also have little to no presence in television. Pacific Islanders makeup a fraction of the characters on prime time. They makeup just 0.2% of acting roles where the character appears regularly. More than 64% of series as of 2017 did not feature a Pacific Islander or Asian American regularly. Their white counterparts will usually get three times the screen time they get in the same program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-asians-on-television-study-20170913-story.html|title=Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders remain underrepresented on television, study finds|last=Braxton|first=Greg|website=latimes.com|access-date=2019-06-07}}</ref>\n\nComic strips in the early 20th century and 19th century had little to no female Refaluwasch whether they be cartoonists or minor characters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/comic-strip|title=Comic strip - Asia and the manga|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n[[Aghurubw|Chief Aghurubw]] (????-????) of the Ghatoliyool clan<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mvariety.com/index.php/special-features/my-marianas/56422-managaha-s-cultural-heritage|title=Marianas Variety - Managaha's cultural heritage|website=mvariety.com|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> and chief of Satawal brought the Refaluwasch in Satawal to CNMI in 1815.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pireport.org/articles/2006/09/19/saipan-carolinians-commemorate-great-leader|title=SAIPAN CAROLINIANS COMMEMORATE GREAT LEADER {{!}} Pacific Islands Report|website=pireport.org|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\nChief Nguschul of Elato (a coral reef atoll consisting of three islands) brought his group to what is now CNMI in 1815 and named a village Ppiyal Oolang which in English means \"beach view sky.\"\n\nFormer Mayor Elias Parong Sablan (1900-1968) became second mayor of Saipan in 1945 and served 3 four-year terms until 1957.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/overcoming-the-odds-a-look-at-uncle-daves-new-book/|title=Overcoming the odds: A look at Uncle Dave's new book|date=2015-03-12|website=Saipan News, Headlines, Events, Ads {{!}} Saipan Tribune|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AQePDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=elias+p+sablan+death#v=onepage&q=elias%20parong%20sablan&f=false|title=A Degree of Success through Curiosity: True Story of a Young Boy Eager to Learn and Find His Calling in Life|last=Sablan|first=David M.|date=2017-03-07|publisher=Dorrance Publishing|isbn=9781480937109}}</ref> He was also Judge of Saipan's Community Court, Chairman of Saipan's Board of Education, Chief of Police, and member of Congress (Saipan's). The man also owned a grocery store.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1955/09/03/saipans-sablan|title=Saipan's Sablan|last=Hellman|first=Geoffrey T.|date=1955-08-27|access-date=2019-05-16|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n[[File:Mau Piailug.gif|thumb|Picture of Piailug in his latter years.]]\n[[Mau Piailug]] (1932-2010) was a master navigator involve in using non-instrument wayfinding.\n\nLarry Saralu was one of the most famous singers in the early Post World War II years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/guampedia/docs/recent_history|title=Recent History|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref> He was Saipanese Carolinian.\n\nLino (Urushemeyoung) Mettao Olopai<ref>Taman, Candido B. et al. A House Commemorative Resolution. ''House Of Representatives.'' 2006, http://cnmileg.gov.mp/documents/house/hse_comres/15/HCR15-17.pdf</ref> (1940-) was responsible for maintaining the Carolinian culture.\n\nBenigno Repeki Fitial (1945-) became the first Carolinian governor of CNMI in 2006 and served until 2013. During this time he was a member of the U. S. Republican Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://classic.nga.org/cms/benigno-fitial|title=Ben\u00edgno Fitial|website=classic.nga.org|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref>\n\nCandy Taman (1948- ) is a Chamorro-Carolinian recording artist who made Chamorro and Carolinian music. He formed a band called Local Breed with Frank \"Bokonggo\" Pangelinan. He would later rename it Tropocisette. He pioneered Chamorro music on CNMI.\n\nThe first Refaluwasch woman to become a lawyer was Jacinta (Cinta) Matagolai<ref>Black, P. Other People's Nostalgia, Other People's Pride. ''The Contemporary Pacific,'' 2000. Accessed 26-03-2019.</ref> Kaipat.\n\nJoseph James Norita Camacho became the first Carolinian judge in CNMI.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/bda46235-1dfb-11e4-aedf-250bc8c9958e/|title=Camacho takes his oath in Carolinian\u2014a first|date=2011-11-18|website=Saipan News, Headlines, Events, Ads {{!}} Saipan Tribune|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> He became a judge in 2011.\n\nSarilyn Ogumoro Escobar became the first Carolinian to be a commissioned [http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/49801-first-carolinian-to-be-a-commissioned-officer-in-us-navy.php officer] in US Navy.<ref>Press Release. \"First Carolinian to be a commissioned officer in US Navy\" ''Marianas Variety.'' 2012, http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/49801-first-carolinian-to-be-a-commissioned-officer-in-us-navy.php</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Allen, Stewart D. & Amesbury, Judith R. Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands As a Fishing Community. ''NOAA''.  2012, https://www.pifsc.noaa.gov/library/pubs/tech/NOAA_Tech_Memo_PIFSC_36.pdf\n*Bagnol, Raquel C. Managaha's cultural heritage. ''Marianas Variety''. 2013, http://www.mvariety.com/index.php/special-features/my-marianas/56422-managaha-s-cultural-heritage\n*Carrell, Toni L. Micronesia Submerged Cultural Resources Assessment. ''NPS.'' 1991'',''https://www.nps.gov/orgs/1635/upload/NNPS_903_D161_-37387.pdf\n*Collier, R. Navigating Modernity / The Carolinians, a tiny group of islanders on Saipan, in the western Pacific, have seen their ancient culture succumb to consumerism. As they try to salvage what they can of their past, they are helping to lead a cultural revival am. ''SF Gate.''1999, https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Navigating-Modernity-The-Carolinians-a-tiny-3774200.php\n*\"Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands.\" ''Department of the Interior,'' https://www.doi.gov/oia/islands/cnmi<nowiki/>Accessed 3 April 2019.\n*James Ellis, S. Saipan Carolinian, One Chuukic Language Blended From Many. ''University Of Hawaii''. 2012, http://www.ling.hawaii.edu/graduate/Dissertations/JimEllisFinal.pdf\n*Encinares, Erwin. Tudela: Indigenous Affairs Expo a success. ''Saipan Tribune.'' 2018, https://www.saipantribune.com/index.php/tudela-indigenous-affairs-expo-a-success/\n*Frain, Sylvia C. 'Make America Secure'. ''Pacific Media Centre.'' 2018, https://ojs.aut.ac.nz/pacific-journalism-review/article/download/407/629/\n*Lirio, Lori Lyn C. 2nd Indigenous Cultural Expo bigger than last year's. ''Marianas Variety.'' 2018, http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/108113-2nd-indigenous-cultural-expo-bigger-than-last-year-s\n*Manabat, B. Flame Tree Arts Festival honors 11 artists, cultural advocates. ''Marianas Variety.'' 2016, http://www.mvariety.com/cnmi/cnmi-news/local/85452-flame-tree-arts-festival-honors-11-artists-cultural-advocates\n*Severance, Craig. Customary Exchange Maintains Cultural Continuity. ''Pacific Islands Fishery News.'' 2010, https://www.wpcouncil.org/outreach/newsletters/PIFN_summer2010.pdf\n*CNMI Supreme Court. In The Matter Of The Estate of Aguida Amires. ''Supreme Court CNMI''. 1996, http://www.cnmilaw.org/pdf/supreme/1997-MP-08.pdf\n*Taman, Candido B. et al. A House Commemorative Resolution. ''House Of Representatives.'' 2006, http://cnmileg.gov.mp/documents/house/hse_comres/15/HCR15-17.pdf\n*{{cite web |title=Joshua Project Carolinian of Northern Mariana Islands Ethnic People Prolife | url=http://www.joshuaproject.net/peopctry.php?rog3=CQ&rop3=101890 | accessdate=December 1, 2008 }}\n*{{cite web |title=Saipan History & Culture |url=http://www.castleresorts.com/Home/vacation/micronesia/saipan?sid=50 |accessdate=December 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006172844/http://www.castleresorts.com/Home/vacation/micronesia/saipan?sid=50 |archivedate=October 6, 2008 }}\n*{{cite web|title=NEA National Heritage Fellowships: Felipe I. and Joseph K. Ruak, Carolinian stick dancers |url=http://www.nea.gov/honors/heritage/fellows/fellow.php?id=2003_08 |accessdate=December 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005134438/http://www.nea.gov///honors/heritage/fellows/fellow.php?id=2003_08 |archivedate=October 5, 2008 }}\n*[http://www.theinsularempire.com ''\"The Insular Empire: America in the Mariana Islands\"''], a one-hour PBS documentary distributed by [http://www.newday.com/films/theinsularempire.html New Day Films]. Directed by Vanessa Warheit. New Day Films, 2010.\n*{{cite web |title=Pacific Footsteps Program Four | url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/arts/radioeye/features/pacificfootsteps/program4.htm | accessdate=December 1, 2008 }}\n*{{cite web|title=CNMI Tanapag --Onwards:People |url=http://www.pacificworlds.com/cnmi/onwards/newfolk.cfm |accessdate=December 3, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006040801/http://www.pacificworlds.com/cnmi/onwards/newfolk.cfm |archivedate=October 6, 2008 }}\n*Goetzfridt, Nicholas J. \"Carolinians on Guam\". ''Guampedia.'' n.d., https://www.guampedia.com/carolinians-on-guam/ Retrieved on March 11, 2019.\n*Lirio, Lori Lyn C. \"September proclaimed Chamorro and Carolinian Cultural Heritage Month\". ''The Guam Daily Post''. 2018, https://www.postguam.com/news/cnmi/september-proclaimed-chamorro-and-carolinian-cultural-heritage-month/article_bc820b5e-aff9-11e8-970b-f3ce9c49a4fc.html Retrieved on March 11, 2019.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carolinian People}}\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Federated States of Micronesia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Northern Mariana Islands]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples of Micronesia]]\n[[Category:Northern Mariana Islands people of Carolinian descent]]\n[[Category:Micronesia]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carolinian_people"}
{"title_page": "Dynoro", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Dynoro\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Edvinas Pechovskis\n| alias            = Dynoro\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1999|12|25}}\n| birth_place      = [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]]\n| origin           = [[Lithuania]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date first) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Electronic music|Electronic]], [[Brazilian bass]]\n| occupation       = [[DJ]], [[Music Producer]]\n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = B1 Recordings, [[Arista Records]] (Sony)\n| associated_acts  = [[Gigi D'Agostino]], [[Ina Wroldsen]], [[Ti\u00ebsto]], [[Alok]]\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} or {{Official URL}} -->\n| module           = \n| module2          = \n| module3          = \n}}\n'''Edvinas Pechovskis'''<ref>[https://www.lrytas.lt/zmones/muzika/2018/07/21/news/netiketa-sekme-lietuvio-irasyta-daina-populiariausia-vokietijoje-7033936/ \u201eLietuvos Rytas\u201c, 2018-07-21 17:55]</ref> (born 25 December 1999 in [[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]]), known professionally as '''Dynoro''', is a Lithuanian music producer. He is best known for his international hit, \"[[In My Mind (Dynoro and Gigi D'Agostino song)|In My Mind]]\", which interpolates the hook from \"[[L'amour toujours]]\" by Italian DJ [[Gigi D'Agostino]].<ref>[http://www.laparisiennelife.com/2018/06/dynoro-se-fait-un-nom-avec-in-my-mind.html Le Parisien Life: Dynoro se fait un nom avec \"In My Mind\"!] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nDynoro started releasing tracks and remixes on [[SoundCloud]] and [[Spotify]] in 2013, gaining fame in [[Lithuania]] thanks to a DJ YouTube channel \"Lithuania HQ\" . In December 2017, his song \"In My Mind\" was released. It was a mashup of the 2012 song of the same name by [[Ivan Gough]], [[Feenixpawl]] and [[Georgi Kay]] and Gigi D'Agostino's single \"L'amour toujours\" from 2000. The song got a lot of attention all over Europe. Due to copyright reasons, the single was taken down from the stores and was re-released in June 2018 with Gigi D'Agostino added as featuring artist.<ref>[http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Dynoro/news-107856.html Charts in France: \"In My Mind\" - Dynoro et Gigi D'Agostino font danser l'Europe avec leur tube \u00e9lectro] {{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nw.de/blogs/literatur_und_musik/musik/22209627_Illegaler-Charthit-Was-steckt-hinter-dem-Nummer-1-Song-In-My-Mind.html llegaler Charthit: Was steckt hinter dem Nummer-1-Song \"In My Mind\"?]</ref> The new version was released on B1 Recordings, a joint venture with [[Sony Music]]. In July 2018, the song reached number one in the German music charts. It was also a number 1 hit in the [[Czech Republic]], [[Finland]], [[Hungary]], [[Slovakia]], [[Sweden]], [[Switzerland]], [[Latvia]], [[Norway]] and a top 5 hit in [[Belgium]], [[Ireland]], [[The Netherlands]], [[The UK]], [[Romania]], [[Poland]] and [[Ukraine]].\n\n==Discography==\n'''Charting singles'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! colspan=\"11\" | Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br /><small>([[List of music recording sales certifications|sales thresholds]])</small>\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|AUT]]<br><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://austriancharts.at/search.asp?search=Dynoro&cat=s|title=Austrian peaks|publisher=Austriancharts.at|access-date=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL]]<br><ref name=\"belgium\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/search.asp?search=Gigi%20D%27Agostino&cat=s |title=Belgian peaks |publisher=Ultratop.be |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Hitlisten|DEN]]<br><ref name=den>{{cite web|url=http://danishcharts.dk/search.asp?search=Dynoro&cat=s|title=Danish peaks|publisher=Danishcharts.dk|accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br><ref name=fr>{{cite web |url=http://lescharts.com/search.asp?search=dynoro&cat=s |title=French peaks |publisher=Lescharts.com |accessdate=2012-06-06}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de|title=Official German Charts|publisher=Offiziellecharts.de|accessdate=May 17, 2019}} Type \"Dynoro\" on the ''suche'' (search) option to see results.</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Dynoro&cat=s|title=Irish peaks|publisher=Irish-charts.com|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|ITA]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://italiancharts.com/showperson.asp?name=Dynoro|title=Italian peaks|publisher=Italiancharts.com|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Single Top 100|NLD]]<br><ref name=nld>{{cite web |url=http://dutchcharts.nl/search.asp?search=dynoro&cat=s |title=Dutch peaks |publisher=Dutchcharts.nl |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[VG-lista|NOR]]<br><ref name=nor>{{cite web |url=http://norwegiancharts.com/search.asp?search=dynoro&cat=s |title=Norwegian peaks |publisher=Norwegiancharts.com |accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Swiss Hitparade|SWI]]<br><ref name=swi>{{cite web |url=http://hitparade.ch/search.asp?search=dynoro&cat=s |title=Swiss peaks |publisher=Hitparade.ch |accessdate=2018-09-02 }}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/54016/dynoro-and-gigi-dagostino|title=DYNORO & GIGI D'AGOSTINO - full Official Chart History|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[In My Mind (Dynoro and Gigi D'Agostino song)|In My Mind]]\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2018\n| 29\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{n/a|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[In My Mind (Dynoro and Gigi D'Agostino song)|In My Mind]]\" <br>{{small|(with [[Gigi D'Agostino]])}}\n| 1\n| 2\n| 4\n| 7\n| 1\n| 5\n| 11\n| 3\n| 1\n| 1\n| 5\n|\n* [[Belgian Entertainment Association|BEA]]: 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/goud-platina/2019/singles|title=Goud en Platina - Singles 2019|website=ultratop.be (Dutch)|accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: Platinum<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified|title=BRIT Certified|website=bpi.co.uk|accessdate=May 17, 2019}} Type \"Dynoro & Gigi D'Agostino\" on the ''Search BPI Awards'' field and click on ''Apply'' to see the result.</ref>\n* [[Bundesverband Musikindustrie|BVMI]]: Diamond<ref name=\"BVMI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.musikindustrie.de/markt-bestseller/gold-/platin-und-diamond-auszeichnung/datenbank/?action=suche&strInterpret=Dynoro&strTtArt=alle&strAwards=checked|title=Gold-/Platin-Datenbank|accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]]: 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"FIMI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fimi.it/top-of-the-music/certificazioni/certificazioni.kl#/certifications|title=Certificazioni|accessdate=27 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI AUT]]: 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ifpi.at/auszeichnungen/?fwp_interpret=Dynoro&fwp_titel=In%20My%20Mind%20(Single)|title